            <section class="prose mt-10">
              <h2>How the debt avalanche method works</h2>
              <p>
                The debt avalanche method is a payoff strategy that minimizes
                the total interest you pay. You make minimum payments on all
                debts, then send every extra dollar to the debt with the
                <strong>highest interest rate</strong>. Once that debt is gone,
                you “roll” its payment into the next‑highest rate, and so on.
              </p>
              <p>
                Compared with the popular debt snowball method (which targets
                the smallest balance first), the avalanche is usually:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Cheaper</strong> – you pay less interest overall.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Often faster</strong> – you become debt‑free sooner.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>More efficient</strong> – every dollar works harder
                  against interest.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Formulas used in this calculator</h2>
              <p>
                For each debt we assume a fixed annual percentage rate (APR)
                with monthly compounding. The monthly interest rate is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>Monthly rate \( r = \dfrac{\text{APR}}{100 \times 12} \)</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Each month we compute the interest and principal portions of
                your payment:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  Interest\(_{\text{month}}\) \( = \text{Balance}_{\text{start}}
                  \times r \)
                </p>
                <p>
                  Principal\(_{\text{month}}\) \( = \text{Payment} -
                  \text{Interest}_{\text{month}} \)
                </p>
                <p>
                  New balance \( = \text{Balance}_{\text{start}} -
                  \text{Principal}_{\text{month}} \)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                The calculator enforces that each debt’s payment is at least its
                minimum payment and at least the interest due, so balances
                always move in the right direction.
              </p>

              <h3>Minimum payment rules</h3>
              <p>
                Many lenders set minimum payments as the greater of a flat
                dollar amount or a percentage of the balance. To keep things
                flexible, this tool lets you:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Enter a fixed minimum payment, or</li>
                <li>
                  Use a percentage‑based rule (e.g., 2% of balance, with a $25
                  floor) by adjusting the minimum as your balance changes.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                For simplicity, this calculator treats the “Min payment” field
                as the <strong>current minimum</strong>. If you want to mimic a
                percentage rule, you can periodically update the inputs as your
                balances fall.
              </p>

              <h2>Debt avalanche vs. debt snowball</h2>
              <p>
                Both methods use the same total monthly budget; they only differ
                in which debt gets the extra payment.
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Debt avalanche:</strong> highest APR first. Best for
                  minimizing interest and usually fastest overall.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Debt snowball:</strong> smallest balance first. Best
                  for quick psychological wins and motivation.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Our calculator runs
                <strong>both strategies in parallel</strong> and shows:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Total interest paid under each method.</li>
                <li>How many months each takes to become debt‑free.</li>
                <li>
                  How much interest and time the avalanche saves vs. the
                  snowball.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Tips for using the results</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Check your minimums:</strong> Make sure the “Min
                  payment” for each debt matches your latest statement.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Don’t add new debt:</strong> The schedule assumes you
                  stop using these credit lines.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Re‑run after changes:</strong> If interest rates or
                  minimums change, update the inputs and recalculate.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Automate payments:</strong> Setting up automatic
                  payments aligned with your plan reduces the chance of missed
                  payments.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Limitations and assumptions</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Interest is approximated with monthly compounding at a fixed
                  APR.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Fees, penalty rates, and daily compounding are not modeled
                  explicitly.
                </li>
                <li>
                  We assume you make the same total payment every month until
                  all debts are paid.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Results are for planning and education only and are not
                  financial advice.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>

